[
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q085",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "motherboard",
    "stem": "In most IBM PCs, the CPU, the device drives, memory expansion slots and active components are mounted on a single board. What is the name of this board?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Motherboard",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Breadboard",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Daughter board",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Grandmother board",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "The single board carrying the CPU, memory expansion slots, drive interfaces, and active components is the motherboard, by definition the main board everything else attaches to. Same fact as the previous item, asked from the component-list direction.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 15
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "7d0ac9dd697d32d2175d6c45e06d2c61ea7e00bd"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q086",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "general-it",
    "subtopic": "computer-types",
    "stem": "What is meant by a dedicated computer?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Which is used by one person only",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Which is assigned one and only one task",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Which uses one kind of software",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Which is meant for application software",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "A dedicated computer is one assigned to a single task or function, for example an embedded controller or a dedicated word processor. 'Used by one person only' is the trap: that is the definition of a personal computer, which can still run any number of different tasks.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 16
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "6722b4c4e917b7fad753c2e3f534fd0c0c57e991"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q087",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "pc-hardware",
    "stem": "The system unit of a personal computer typically contains all of the following except:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Microprocessor",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Disk controller",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Serial interface",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Modem",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "The system unit houses the microprocessor, the disk controller, and the serial interface, so those three are all inside; the modem is the exception because it is classically an external device (or an add-on card) that connects the machine to a phone line. Note this is a dated question: internal modem cards do exist, but the exam key treats the modem as the outside-the-box item.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 17
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "0758d07377e6dcb96ad3639d9ce20f3d44766217"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q088",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "programming",
    "subtopic": "compilers",
    "stem": "A computer program that converts an entire program into machine language is called a/an",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Interpreter",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Simulator",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Compiler",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Commander",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "A compiler translates the entire source program into machine code in one pass before any of it runs, producing an object or executable file. The interpreter distractor is the direct contrast: it works one statement at a time (see the next question).",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 18
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "2ddd79a18ddf16c348b22e9f0ba97a821f8720ed"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q089",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "programming",
    "subtopic": "compilers",
    "stem": "A computer program that translates one program instructions at a time into machine language is called a/an",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Interpreter",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "CPU",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Compiler",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Simulator",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "An interpreter reads, translates, and executes one instruction at a time, with no separate whole-program translation step and no executable file left behind. This is the exact complement of the compiler in the previous item: whole program at once = compiler, one statement at a time = interpreter.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 19
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "4e8f6b4d48fd4dbd23663b6a77db2fcb5cc34983"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q090",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "general-it",
    "subtopic": "computer-terminology",
    "stem": "A small or intelligent device is so called because it contains within it a",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Computer",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Microcomputer",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Programmable",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Sensor",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Answer unverified: the circulated key marks D (Sensor), but the review panel resolved to B (Microcomputer). A device is called smart or intelligent because it embeds computation, that is a microcomputer (microprocessor plus memory and I/O) small enough to fit inside it; a sensor only transduces a physical quantity and confers no intelligence on its own. If the grader follows the printed key, expect D; on the merits the answer is B.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 20
    },
    "keyProvenance": "derived",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "derived",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "2137642c566bfd81da81b5ee7b0601a91e1fac87"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q091",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "computer-architecture",
    "subtopic": "cpu-components",
    "stem": "The ALU of a computer responds to the commands coming from",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Primary memory",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Control section",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "External memory",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Cache memory",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "The control unit decodes each instruction and issues the control signals that tell the ALU which operation to perform, so the ALU responds to the control section. Memory (primary, cache, or external) only supplies operands and instructions; it does not command the ALU.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 1
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "f0b60458d54b633770ba2caa8adfc9e0d46de026"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q092",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "memory-operations",
    "stem": "The act of retrieving existing data from memory is called",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Read-out",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Read from",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Read",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of above",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "'Read', 'read-out', and 'read-from' are all accepted names for the operation of retrieving data already stored in memory, so 'All of above' is correct. Note that reading is non-destructive in modern memory: the data stays in place, unlike a write, which overwrites it.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 2
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "10d2314dfa8e1f577ceee29607db0952d2c8d7a8"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q093",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "general-it",
    "subtopic": "computer-basics",
    "stem": "All modern computer operate on",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Information",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Floppies",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Data",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Word",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "Computers operate on data: raw, unprocessed values. Trap: \"Information\" is the classic distractor because information is what data becomes after processing, so it is the output, not the material the machine works on.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 3
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "0af5da60e8c1d5e41aa46a77d1e55b503f2fa6e3"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q094",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "computer-architecture",
    "subtopic": "instruction-format",
    "stem": "Instructions and memory address are represented by",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Character code",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Binary codes",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Binary word",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Parity bit",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Everything inside the machine, both the instructions and the addresses they refer to, is held as patterns of 0s and 1s, i.e. binary codes. Character code (like ASCII) encodes text only, a binary word names a unit of storage rather than a representation, and a parity bit is only for error detection.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "c538b7d7358934c29d0d36257f989f21d2fe5001"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q095",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "character-encoding",
    "stem": "Which of the following code used in present day computing was developed by IBM Corporation?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "ASCII",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Hollerith Code",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Baudot Code",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "EBCDIC Code",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "EBCDIC (Extended Binary Coded Decimal Interchange Code) was created by IBM for the System/360 and is still used on IBM mainframes today. Trap: Hollerith code is also IBM-lineage (punched cards) but it is obsolete, and the stem says \"used in present day computing\"; ASCII is an ANSI standard and Baudot came from telegraphy.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "696c0bbd111b20281678be961de4b0f7f0f760c8"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q096",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "optical-media",
    "stem": "What is the latest write-once optical storage media?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Digital paper",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Magneto-optical disk",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "WORM disk",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "CD-ROM disk",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Answer unverified: the printed key says CD-ROM, but CD-ROM is factory-pressed read-only media, not write-once, and magneto-optical disks are rewritable. Applying the stem literally, the only write-once optical media listed are WORM disk (early 1980s) and digital paper (around 1990), so \"latest write-once\" points to digital paper, and the keyed answer is self-contradictory.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 6
    },
    "keyProvenance": "derived",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "derived",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "bc37d67c4ee44eecf93cfeb106e66dbf8a9194cf"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q097",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "storage-media",
    "stem": "The most important advantage of a video disk is",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Compactness",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Potential capacity",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Durability",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Cost effectiveness",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "The videodisc's headline advantage over the magnetic media of its era was the sheer amount it could hold, i.e. its potential capacity. It was neither cheap nor especially compact compared with the alternatives, so those distractors fail.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
